==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hymen
<hw>Hy"men</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>"ymh`n</grk>
skin, membrane.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A fold of mucous membrane
often found at the orifice of the vagina in virgins; the vaginal
membrane. It is usually torn by sexual intercourse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hymen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hymen
<hw>Hy"men</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Class Myth.)</fld> <def>A fabulous deity; according to some, the
son of Apollo and Urania, according to others, of Bacchus and Venus. He
was the god of marriage, and presided over nuptial
solemnities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till <qex>Hymen</qex> brought his love-delighted hour,⟦br⟧
There dwelt no joy in Eden's rosy bower.</q>
<rj><qau>Campbell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Marriage; union as if by marriage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hymen</qex> of element and race.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj></p>

<p><ent>hymenal</ent>⟦br⟧
